    <item>
      <title>14.24 Houkou</title>
      <link>https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-24-houkou/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-24-houkou/</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 22 Feb 2025 04:20:45 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;main class="wp-block-group is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow"&gt; &lt;div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"&gt;&lt;h1 class="wp-block-post-title"&gt;14.24 Houkou&lt;/h1&gt;   &lt;div style="height:1px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;div class="entry-content wp-block-post-content is-layout-constrained wp-block-post-content-is-layout-constrained"&gt; &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-23-the-criminal/"&gt;Previous Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was guided to an estate in the capital. Although she had no idea whose residence it was, it smelt heavily of medicine.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Where are we?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Court Physician Lao’s hoome,” Chue answered.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Despite its simplicity, the estate had a historical feel.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Kokuyou got stabbed in the stomach, but he’s conscious and eating heartily. He seemed well, so they had him moved to the capitaaal.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As he got stabbed, there was no way he could be left in a village that was full of patients. When considering the inquiries to come, moving him to the capital would make things easier. She understood why people would want him quarantined for the moment despite his resistance to smallpox. Since Court Physician Lao has experience with smallpox, his family should also understand the disease.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“He’s been moved here temporarily since Maomao-san and Yo-san were at the clinic.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao understood the situation.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Court Physician Lao’s family and servants kept their heads down and didn’t move when Maomao and Chue walked past them.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;It’s best we don’t greet them—that&amp;#8217;s the feel I&amp;#8217;m getting.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was probably better to not get into contact with people involved with smallpox.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;They headed for the room at the back.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Here we are. He’s insiiide.” Chue stopped in front of the room.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Are you not going in, Chue-san?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Let’s seee, Chue-san would prefer to not have Maomao-san alone with him, but is it fine to join you?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chue was perceptive. She was probably referring to what Maomao would chat about with Kokuyou now.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Please let me know if there’s anything. The quick and agile Chue-san will come to rescue you, Maomao-saaan.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Thank you,” Maomao said, and entered the room alone.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou was lying in bed, reading a book.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Hey,” he said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s not, &lt;em&gt;hey&lt;/em&gt;. I heard you got stabbed.” Maomao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yup, wanna see the injuryyy?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“No need. You seem well.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou was the same.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Just now, I met the person who stabbed Kokuyou,” she said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ahhh, the village head, riiight? His looks changed a lot so I didn’t recognise him at first.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“He called you a Houkou.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“A Houkou?” Kokuyou tilted his head in confusion.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s a mythical creature. A parasitic monster that lives in a thousand year old tree.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Oh? How is that me?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Looks like Kokuyou really didn’t know.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao thought she didn’t know either. “Do you know what a Yamabiko is?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I know that one. It’s the thing that returns your voice in the mountains, right?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“If I call the tree spirit, a Kodama &lt;sub&gt;(echo)&lt;/sub&gt;, do you understand?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Oh yeah, people call it that too, don’t they?” Kokuyou continued to chat with a grin. Maomao didn’t see him as a bad person. Was their first meeting at the docks?&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was Maomao’s group who allowed Kokuyou to board the boat. She remembered how Kokuyou had given motion sickness medicine to Rahan, who had been suffering from seasickness, in return.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;When was the next time they met?&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao had asked him to watch over the apothecary in Verdigris Mansion since she had been concerned for Sazen. That time, he took it up since she paid him.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;And recently, he was able to get a court physician-like job through Maomao’s introduction. Seems like the pay was so good that he was doing a good job.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You seem to have a good relationship with Yo-san’s family.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yup, Yo and her family were very good to me.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“So that’s why you vaccinated them against smallpox and taught them all sorts of medical skills.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yup.” Kokuyou put down his book. It seemed to be related to medical skills.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Then, how were you with the village head and the other villagers who were not nice?” Maomao clenched her fist.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;I did my best to not associate with theeem.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“And when they harassed you?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou let out a groan. “Can I not answer? I want to stay friends with Maomao-saan.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao froze. “Was it you, Kokuyou, who spread smallpox in Yo’s village?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Nooo, but you know, I thought I wouldn’t need to pay them back if I was gone. And then, in actual fact, the village head did drive me out.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou did nothing to the villagers. He chose to do nothing as payback. He thought the village head would die as well, but contrary to expectations, the witch doctor survived in addition to Yo’s family.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It wasn’t that the village head was lucky. He might have already caught smallpox before. The pockmarks Maomao saw were quite old.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Yamabiko. Kodama. Houkou. She now understood why the village head called Kokuyou that.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Repay kindness with kindness, malice with malice.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;That was all there was to it. Like how the mountains would echo back your calls. Like a mirror, he only reflected back the hearts of others.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;And that’s why he’s good at bargaining.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The reason Maomao saw Kokuyou as a good person, was probably because Kokuyou saw her treatment of him as good.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;In that case, Maomao could see what happened to people who treated Kokuyou with malice.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“When did Kokuyou catch smallpox?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Over ten years agooo.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Then, from where did you get the smallpox you used to vaccinate Yo and her family?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Smallpox scabs were highly infectious, but only for about a year.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou cracked a smile, and took off the cloth that covered half his face. His handsome face was dense with pockmarks. “Can you see any other scars aside from the pockmarks?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Did you get hit by something?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I got hit by a club. The robber stripped me of all of my possessions, you seee.” There was no change in his tone. Kokuyou was cheery as usual. “I was lucky it was spring. If it was summer or winter, I think I would’ve died. I staggered around looking for herbs to staunch the bleeding. And was about near dead when I sought help from a village nearby. They were such nice people. They nursed someone like me back to health. But you know, the other villagers couldn’t stand the sight of me and tried to drive me out. That’s right. It was because the robber who stole from me was in that group.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As always, the story Kokuyou told light-heartedly was horrible.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“So it was inevitable he got in my way. He pretended to not know me, and tried to chase me out before I recognised him. It was hilarious and amusing, but when he tried to gag me, I paid him back with one thing.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What sort of payback?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I made him into a seedbed.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was sharp enough to know not to ask what kind of seedbed he was turned into. In order to lower the risk of the smallpox vaccination, you would need a healthy body and environment that allowed nursing.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Surely a seedbed wouldn’t need such things.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;I would bring up the topic of mercy, but it was the other person who made the first move.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yup, and I didn&amp;#8217;t think the other villagers would hear me out.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She couldn’t completely dismiss the way Kokuyou did things. However, it seems like he had no restraint.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Then, did you give the village head of Yo-san’s village payback?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I was the one who got stabbed by the village head.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“No, you did something, right? Otherwise it wouldn’t explain why the village head was that weakened. He probably doesn’t have more than a few days left.” Maomao had her suspicions. The village head had declined so much as to smell of death. He had been trembling, unable to articulate, and hallucinating.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;He looked nothing like someone who had the energy to move from the capital to the smallpox village to stab Kokuyou.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;He could only have been poisoned.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“The village head made strange fragrances and medicine that he called speeells.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Was it ergot?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Correct. How did you knooow?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“The village head’s fingers were necrotic.” She had no idea if Kokuyou administered ergot or a different poison.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“He stabbed me first, so I stuffed the poison he was carrying into his mouth. He served me that many times when I was in the village. My younger brother always told me to do unto others as what had been done unto you.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Your younger brother?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“My younger brother. My twin who died and left me behind.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was something she heard before. “You two were inoculated with different smallpox vaccinations for an experiment, is that right?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yup, I was inoculated with human pus, my younger brother with livestock pus. My brother was fine since he got the weak toxin. As you can see for me, mine aggravated and I nearly died.” Kokuyou touched the pockmarks on his right cheek. “My master who raised us was a brilliant doctor. But, he was cowardly and wouldn’t try out the smallpox vaccination without testing it on us first. It was amazing. He’d never caught the disease even though he’d been studying it for years.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“He probably left all the dangerous work to his disciples,” Maomao said bluntly.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou was a peculiar guy. He was neither benevolent nor malevolent. He only reflected the actions of others like a mirror.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;And yet, despite his cheery voice, he sounded a little gloomy only when he talked about his younger brother.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“My brother would come save me when I got bullied. That time, my brother would get payback for me even if I didn’t. So, I had to get payback too, so I…” Kokuyou put his hands together. “&amp;#8230;switched the animal pus meant for my master into human pus.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…” Maomao gulped.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“My master contracted the serious smallpox. He was in so much grief over the failure of the smallpox vaccination he tested on so many of his disciples that he also burned his research findings, and got weaker and weaker. My brother put him out of his suffering.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou wasn’t dragging out his words as usual.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“My brother died afterwards. Killed himself. Probably because I told him that I switched the smallpox vaccination.” Kokuyou clenched his fist and bowed his head. He seemed to be repenting. “I should’ve lied. I should’ve told him that the experiment failed, should’ve covered it up with a look of innocence.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Can you lie to a mirror?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou shook his head. “I had my brother with me since forever, so I didn’t know what I should do afterwards.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Hence Kokuyou could only be a mirror, reflecting the kindness or malice from others.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;What will Maomao do to me?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“…” The goosebumps had yet to settle. Maomao had thoughts regarding the human called Kokuyou. She probably wouldn’t be able to get along with him in the way she used to.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Then, she shouldn’t have tried to expose him, but she needed to understand the kind of person he was.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;A Houkou-like man.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was as the village head said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou was harmless to harmless people, harmful to harmful people.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Hence the village head deemed that Kokuyou was someone who needed to be dealt with, if not killed.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“One question,” she said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Whaaat?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Was the village head truly a good-for-nothing?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Hmmm, I wonder? At least, he did manage the village well up until the spread of smallpox.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Right&lt;/em&gt;, Maomao thought. The children at Yo’s home had listened to the village head when he came.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What I did is certainly dangerous, so I understand why he told me to stop. He was the one who spearheaded the harassment.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao had no idea what kind of person the village head was. However, she understood a little of how he thought of Kokuyou.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I think it’s unfair.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Kokuyou could cure a disease that couldn’t be cured by spells. Kokuyou treated people so they wouldn’t contract smallpox.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Hence, despite his hate for Kokuyou, the village head copied him. He tried to perform smallpox vaccinations on children. The smallpox scabs from years ago were equivalent to being non-infectious. But, unfortunately due to a child who got infected, it led to this disaster.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;For what he did for the people, he was treated as a random attacker, chased around, and as a result, he must have hated Kokuyou so much.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ahh, what should I do?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The fact that the village head was a criminal didn’t change.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Even if what Kokuyou had done was a crime, it was now too late to charge him.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Above anything else, from now on, Kokuyou would be a useful person in medicine.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;But I don’t want to categorise people as useful or useless.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao had a sly personality.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chue had probably heard this entire conversation. If so, she could only offload it all to the other woman.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I pray that Kokuyou will only be surrounded by good people,” she said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Praying is unlike Maomaooo.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao waved and left the room.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chue was outside the room. She bounced to her feet and her hair swept up. “Anything to report?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Not really.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That’s a pity.” Chue followed after Maomao. “Maomao-san, you look tired. How about we go out for dinner today?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I don’t feel like it.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Pity.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The uneasy feeling continued to plague Maomao.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" /&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;T/N: Yamabiko, which means mountain god, also means echo.&lt;br&gt;Kodama, which means tree spirit, also means echo.&lt;br&gt;Houkou, the Japanese name for the Chinese Penghou, is a tree spirit, which is also associated with the Yamabiko, and so, is also known for its echo&lt;/sup&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;That&amp;#8217;s how the parallels are made in this chapter. &lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sup&gt;This chapter references the Japanese version of the Penghou, in that they are the same type of creature as the Yamabiko and Kodama. All are tree spirits. The Chinese Penghou seems to be a dog-pig thing with a human face, and doesn&amp;#8217;t seems to have the echoing quality that its Japanese counterpart is known for.&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p class="has-text-align-right"&gt;(Next Chapter)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing"&gt;&lt;h3 class="sd-title"&gt;Share this:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="sd-content"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li class="share-facebook"&gt;&lt;div class="fb-share-button" data-href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-24-houkou/" data-layout="button_count"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li class="share-end"&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-130534757-5360-681f534ac6938' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/index.html?ver=20250510#blog_id=130534757&amp;amp;post_id=5360&amp;amp;origin=shikarito.wordpress.com&amp;amp;obj_id=130534757-5360-681f534ac6938' data-name='like-post-frame-130534757-5360-681f534ac6938' data-title='Like or Reblog'&gt;&lt;div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'&gt;&lt;span class='button'&gt;&lt;span&gt;Like&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class='loading'&gt;Loading&amp;#8230;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span class='sd-text-color'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a class='sd-link-color' href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-24-houkou/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</description>
